WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.840
Hi, everybody.

00:00:01.260 --> 00:00:01.560
Okay.

00:00:01.560 --> 00:00:04.560
Thank you all so much for being here, especially after lunch.

00:00:04.560 --> 00:00:07.020
I know, can I, it's all right.

00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:07.840
Thanks for being here on time.

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:10.020
I'm excited to be presenting to you all today.

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:15.800
So in 2018, I was a student at the University of Chicago, which is a picture

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:21.040
of this, and the UChicago Hospital opened or actually reopened their trauma

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:22.959
center after decades of it being closed.

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:26.879
So there was a lot of excitement and hype about this.

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:30.660
So I heard about it kind of in the emails UChicago sent me, you read about in the

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:34.820
news, both kind of at, at the university and then across Chicago as a whole.

00:00:35.099 --> 00:00:38.540
So it sounded like kind of, there was a lot of excitement and I was curious

00:00:38.540 --> 00:00:40.000
about this and wanted to learn more.

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:44.240
So one thing I did is figured out what a trauma center was or kind of what that

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:49.020
meant, so I found out that it, that means that a trauma center is kind of a part

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:53.740
of a hospital often in ER and it's equipped to provide surgery for traumatic

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:56.619
injuries, so things like car crashes, like falls or burns.

00:00:56.939 --> 00:00:59.340
Or potentially things like SABR gunshot wounds.

00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:04.820
So another kind of logical question I had was, so where, where are trauma centers

00:01:04.820 --> 00:01:09.300
in Chicago and where were they before, before the opening of, of the UChicago

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:09.860
trauma center?

00:01:10.139 --> 00:01:15.339
So this is a map kind of showing that distribution before, before the opening.

00:01:15.339 --> 00:01:19.300
So one thing you may know here, or you may notice is on this South side of

00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:24.779
Chicago, there's kind of this dearth of trauma centers, which is potentially a

00:01:24.779 --> 00:01:30.879
concern and as a consequence of the legacy and kind of continued history of

00:01:30.919 --> 00:01:34.919
kind of segregation and discrimination and racism that the South side of

00:01:34.919 --> 00:01:40.199
Chicago faces, there's a high need for, or there was a high need for trauma centers.

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:45.180
So you can see that here with the gunshot wounds and motor vehicle crashes patterning.

00:01:45.839 --> 00:01:50.959
So this, this data comes from this really great article from Crane Chicago Business.

00:01:51.239 --> 00:01:52.760
If you want to learn more, I really recommend it.

00:01:53.059 --> 00:01:56.580
But kind of going through this process and really thinking about this really

00:01:56.739 --> 00:01:57.580
opened my eyes for me.

00:01:57.580 --> 00:02:02.019
And it was the first time I thought seriously about kind of space and access

00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:05.379
and what that meant kind of in a city, in a serious way.

00:02:05.660 --> 00:02:10.059
And I really kind of, it opened my eyes to this form of serious spatial thinking.

00:02:10.139 --> 00:02:14.139
And so kind of as a consequence of this experience in my, in my time early on in

00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:16.740
the university, I decided to study geography.

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:18.740
So shout out to any other geography majors.

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:25.880
And then I ultimately took that thinking to the Urban Institute where I work on the

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:27.080
spatial equity data tool.

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.520
And this is the tool I want to talk to you all about today.

00:02:29.759 --> 00:02:33.960
So kind of why at a high level, did we create the spatial equity data tool?

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:37.399
So we've noticed in the past few years that there's been an increased demand

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:42.559
across governments, across nonprofits and other organizations to reliably

00:02:42.559 --> 00:02:44.559
assess and measure spatial equity.

00:02:44.779 --> 00:02:49.699
And so to respond to that, my team developed the spatial equity tool and then I have

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:52.380
since built on it for the last two years.

00:02:52.779 --> 00:02:55.899
So at a high level, what does the tool do?

00:02:56.740 --> 00:02:58.820
So this is kind of the workflow we think about here.

00:02:59.059 --> 00:03:04.020
So you can upload to the tool any point vector spatial data.

00:03:04.020 --> 00:03:04.820
So what does that mean?

00:03:04.899 --> 00:03:09.580
It means anything that you can plot as a series of individual points on a map.

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:11.699
That's the type of data the tool takes.

00:03:12.479 --> 00:03:17.919
So you upload it to the tool, the tool does a lot of work and then it returns to two sets

00:03:17.919 --> 00:03:22.080
of scores. It returns these demographic disparity scores and geographic disparity

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:23.160
scores. Okay.

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:25.240
So what are those scores?

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:30.000
So this is an example screenshot from our spatial equity data tool for demographic

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:37.000
disparity scores. For the next two slides, we have examples from this New Orleans 311

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.440
call request data from 2014 to 2018.

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:42.860
311 is a service that many cities provide it.

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:47.979
So as you may know, it sounds kind of like 911, but you would call 911 for an emergency.

00:03:48.179 --> 00:03:51.179
311 is a service you could call for kind of non-emergencies.

00:03:51.179 --> 00:03:54.500
So say like your streetlight has gone out or you have a pothole that you need filled.

00:03:54.779 --> 00:04:00.100
311 may be the way you could reach out to your city to to get that service.

00:04:00.339 --> 00:04:01.779
Okay, so that's what 311 is.

00:04:01.899 --> 00:04:03.740
What is this demographic disparity score?

00:04:03.979 --> 00:04:08.419
So what the demographic disparity score does is it looks across the geography as a whole

00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:10.360
and it makes a comparison.

00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:16.359
So we say, hey, looking at, in this case, the census tracks where these points or where

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:21.839
these 311 call requests come from, how do the demographics of those areas compare to

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:22.679
the city as a whole?

00:04:22.920 --> 00:04:23.920
So how to interpret it?

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:29.519
I'm sorry it's small, but the top line is white, non-Latinx residents.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:34.880
And so what this says is comparing kind of those census tracks where most of the data

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:40.459
come from, those areas have disproportionately high numbers of white residents compared to

00:04:40.459 --> 00:04:41.420
the city as a whole.

00:04:42.140 --> 00:04:48.459
Conversely, you can see from the bottom line, which says black, non-Latinx residents, in

00:04:48.459 --> 00:04:52.380
the areas where 311 call requests came from in this time period, those areas were

00:04:52.380 --> 00:04:56.260
disproportionately underrepresented, or black residents were disproportionately

00:04:56.260 --> 00:04:59.260
underrepresented in those areas, at least in this data.

00:04:59.459 --> 00:05:02.980
So that's kind of how to read these demographic disparity scores.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:07.279
Again, zooming out, it's like across the geography, what demographic groups are over

00:05:07.279 --> 00:05:13.239
or underrepresented in their access to kind of the point resource data that's uploaded.

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:17.239
OK, so that's the first set of scores.

00:05:17.359 --> 00:05:20.640
The second set of scores are a geographic disparity score.

00:05:20.959 --> 00:05:24.799
So this looks at something different, whereas the demographic disparity score says, hey,

00:05:24.799 --> 00:05:26.839
let's look across the geography as a whole.

00:05:27.079 --> 00:05:31.160
The geographic disparity score says, I want to look at a specific subgeography.

00:05:31.339 --> 00:05:34.940
So for the city scale, the subgeography, again, is a census tract.

00:05:35.179 --> 00:05:39.700
And we do kind of simple arithmetic, a simple difference in proportions here.

00:05:39.700 --> 00:05:43.619
So we look at the proportion of the data points in a census tract that we upload and the

00:05:43.619 --> 00:05:45.299
proportion of a population.

00:05:45.619 --> 00:05:50.660
So if the proportion of data points is greater than the proportion of the population, that

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:54.660
area receives a positive disparity score and it's colored in blue.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:59.420
And we might think of that as that area is being overrepresented by those points.

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:05.440
Conversely, if there are, if the proportion of data is less than the proportion of the

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:09.880
population, we would say that that area gets a negative disparity score.

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:11.440
So it's kind of the yellow and orange areas.

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:15.040
And we might think that that area is underrepresented by the data.

00:06:16.119 --> 00:06:19.320
OK, so that are geographic disparity scores.

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:21.480
Now, you may ask, why do we like this?

00:06:22.119 --> 00:06:24.160
We think it brings a couple of key benefits.

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:28.480
The first is it makes performing standardized equity analyses easier.

00:06:28.660 --> 00:06:32.019
Right. So you don't have to decide what what it means to have spatial equity.

00:06:32.019 --> 00:06:34.059
We've kind of like made definitions ourselves.

00:06:34.299 --> 00:06:37.260
You can upload your data and we just run the calculations.

00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:41.459
We think it's easy for you to compare across time where you could upload multiple years of

00:06:41.459 --> 00:06:43.299
data. You can compare across geographies.

00:06:43.299 --> 00:06:45.940
So we handle any geographies across the U.S.

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:50.019
And it's fast, it's free and it's reproducible.

00:06:50.339 --> 00:06:54.420
So those are all kind of open source standards that we are excited to follow.

00:06:54.859 --> 00:06:56.679
OK, so what are some use cases?

00:06:56.679 --> 00:06:58.299
How might how might you use this tool?

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:03.059
So we think one key use case is this idea of measuring equity in the allocation of

00:07:03.059 --> 00:07:08.179
place-based programs. So suppose kind of you're interested in putting out a resource

00:07:08.299 --> 00:07:10.540
where this question is, would you want that resource?

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:13.059
I don't know. Maybe where are you trying to put your new trauma center?

00:07:13.299 --> 00:07:17.220
But, you know, these examples to playgrounds, bus shelters, libraries, anything like

00:07:17.220 --> 00:07:23.299
that, you could kind of use those those charts that we made and and make a decision

00:07:23.299 --> 00:07:27.540
based on those. You also could use it to examine the representativeness of program

00:07:27.559 --> 00:07:32.920
participants. So so suppose you're you have a program, you know where the participants

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:38.320
live and you're targeting that program at a broader population, you could use as a

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:43.079
point resource the location of those program participants and then you could compare

00:07:43.079 --> 00:07:44.559
against that that population.

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:47.320
And then lastly, kind of this is a similar logic.

00:07:47.799 --> 00:07:51.359
We think you could identify areas for future investment with the tool.

00:07:52.239 --> 00:07:54.839
OK, so those are use cases.

00:07:55.059 --> 00:07:59.660
Now you might be asking, I hope you're asking, how do you interact with the tool?

00:07:59.859 --> 00:08:04.940
So kind of the paradigm from the inception of the tool to March of twenty twenty four

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:08.940
was this. So you, the user, would go to our website and if you search Spatial Reputee

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:10.220
Data Tool, it'll be the first link.

00:08:10.459 --> 00:08:11.859
I also have a QR code at the end.

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:17.579
But you go to our website, you drag and drop a CSV file, then kind of on the back end

00:08:17.579 --> 00:08:22.380
we have some AWS infrastructure that runs and then we return the results kind of to

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:25.720
the website. The website visualizes those results and you can view them and download

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:27.399
them. Awesome.

00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:31.119
As of March twenty twenty four, we have launched an application programming interface,

00:08:31.119 --> 00:08:33.200
API, so we're super excited about that.

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:38.520
And in now, in addition, you can use our API to get those same calculations.

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:45.200
OK, so with that background, I kind of want to introduce the second phase of my talk

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:50.559
and present this thesis to you, which is that we think identifying the right tool for

00:08:50.559 --> 00:08:52.340
the job can lead to unexpected gains.

00:08:52.539 --> 00:08:56.780
So throughout the development process, the Spatial Reputee Data Tool team and I have

00:08:56.780 --> 00:08:58.700
faced a number of technical problems.

00:08:58.859 --> 00:09:02.979
And then we've kind of thought hard about them and found these technical solutions to

00:09:02.979 --> 00:09:08.619
them. And we think because we found these solutions that work well, we've actually

00:09:08.619 --> 00:09:12.659
received some unexpected gains as a consequence of of using those solutions.

00:09:12.659 --> 00:09:16.979
So I'm really excited to share three examples of the problems we faced, the solution

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.239
that we decided upon and why we decided upon it, and then these exciting, potentially

00:09:21.239 --> 00:09:22.840
unexpected gains, at least for us.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:24.559
OK, so here we go.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.080
So the question number one, the problem we face is where do we run our code?

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:31.559
And this is actually a problem that my colleagues faced before I joined the project.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:39.080
So kind of the starting point here is that we have some Python scripts and the Python

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:41.640
kind of calculates the metrics that we're showing.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:45.000
But there's this question of kind of where where do you run this code?

00:09:45.179 --> 00:09:47.500
And these are the requirements that we're facing.

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:48.859
So we need something to be scalable.

00:09:48.859 --> 00:09:52.260
So right. Hopefully, you know, after this presentation, everybody here is like, I got to

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:55.179
go use this tool. So we have a high, a high demand.

00:09:55.780 --> 00:09:57.380
We also want it to be fast, right?

00:09:57.380 --> 00:10:01.219
This is targeted towards people who, you know, want to upload their data.

00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:04.080
They want to get the results. It's not like you want to email somebody and have them do

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:06.260
the work. So we want something close to real time.

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:07.940
And actually, our script is quite fast.

00:10:08.219 --> 00:10:12.140
So, you know, the the computing environment should be able to respond to that as well.

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:16.239
And we also want something to be cheap, you know, for obvious reasons.

00:10:16.359 --> 00:10:20.359
OK, so the solution we have here is AWS Lambda.

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:26.960
So Lambda is a service that is offered by Amazon Web Services that provides serverless

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:31.520
compute. So it kind of runs the code or the function you write automatically and it

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:33.840
manages the compute resources behind the scene.

00:10:34.719 --> 00:10:36.359
So that's really helpful.

00:10:36.359 --> 00:10:38.479
You don't have to think about servers or anything like that.

00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:41.840
It's fast. So it automatically scales.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:44.299
Right. So as as demand comes in, it scales up.

00:10:44.299 --> 00:10:45.859
It kind of runs more.

00:10:45.859 --> 00:10:48.539
And that's really helpful for this kind of demand issue.

00:10:49.340 --> 00:10:51.900
And then it's cheap. You only are charged for what you use.

00:10:51.900 --> 00:10:55.059
And actually, the the rate is is quite affordable for us.

00:10:55.059 --> 00:10:57.219
So so that's really helpful.

00:10:57.380 --> 00:11:02.739
One thing you may know about AWS Lambda, one potential limitation for use cases is that

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:07.780
it's it's only runs for 15 minutes.

00:11:07.780 --> 00:11:09.260
After 15 minutes, it stops running.

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:11.559
But this isn't a problem for us because our code is very fast.

00:11:11.559 --> 00:11:13.359
It takes like under 10 seconds.

00:11:13.359 --> 00:11:14.440
So that's kind of not a problem.

00:11:14.719 --> 00:11:15.799
OK, so that was our problem.

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:18.440
Here's our solution. What is our unexpected gain?

00:11:18.760 --> 00:11:24.719
So as we were expanding the Spatial Equity Data tool to respond to the API, we kind of

00:11:24.719 --> 00:11:27.599
had to expand the logic of the code.

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:31.440
So we were kind of looking for ways where, hey, you know, if you run your old code, it

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:35.320
works as well. But if we have these new inputs from kind of that look a little bit

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:39.380
different or that have different structure, we need to use some logic to handle those.

00:11:39.619 --> 00:11:45.659
And so kind of the solution that we found are a second AWS service called Step Functions.

00:11:45.659 --> 00:11:50.380
So Step Functions are a service that allows you to create a series of tasks of steps and

00:11:50.380 --> 00:11:51.460
then orchestrate them.

00:11:51.619 --> 00:11:54.979
And really importantly, Lambda Functions can be those steps.

00:11:55.619 --> 00:12:00.340
And so part of the Step Function that we really appreciate is there is this control flow

00:12:00.340 --> 00:12:04.580
logic. So depending on the output of one function, you can do one thing or do another

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:08.479
thing. So it's kind of just like an if-else branch, but kind of at a different scale.

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:13.039
So that was really helpful for us to kind of handle requests either from the web interface

00:12:13.039 --> 00:12:14.119
or from the API.

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:18.440
And our unexpected benefit here, at least for our team, when we kind of learned about and

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:23.840
then implemented the solution, is that there's really elegant integration of Lambda

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:27.080
Functions. So it's really easy for us to kind of incorporate that software we had.

00:12:27.320 --> 00:12:30.679
We don't need to make that much changes to the Lambda Function, but then we can just

00:12:30.700 --> 00:12:35.340
build on it in an easy way for as we added the new functionality.

00:12:35.500 --> 00:12:40.260
So not to worry, this is an open source conference, so the next solutions will be open

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:41.539
source and Posit themed.

00:12:42.539 --> 00:12:46.140
So now we have this question, how do you document our API?

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:49.619
And actually, the answer may have been revealed yesterday, but nonetheless, we're doing it

00:12:49.619 --> 00:12:54.140
anyway. So the requirements here are we want to handle code, right?

00:12:54.140 --> 00:12:59.059
We have an API. We want to have code showing how to interact with the API.

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:04.440
We also kind of APIs are these like it's hard to capture them or to show them.

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:08.719
Right. So we want a home page where you can go, you know, that we can direct people to

00:13:08.719 --> 00:13:14.359
for the API. And then also we had really excellent documentation, but in the form of a

00:13:14.359 --> 00:13:18.679
PDF text and we wanted to kind of find a more updated home for that, that maybe it's a

00:13:18.679 --> 00:13:20.840
little bit easier to interact with on the web.

00:13:21.719 --> 00:13:26.760
OK, so perhaps unsurprisingly, our solution here is a Quarto book.

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:28.580
So, right. It handles code.

00:13:28.580 --> 00:13:31.979
You can do code integration in Quarto and HTML.

00:13:32.619 --> 00:13:33.940
It serves as a home page.

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:36.140
We just have a chapter in our book that's about the chapter.

00:13:36.979 --> 00:13:39.260
And then, of course, it handles text really nicely.

00:13:40.179 --> 00:13:41.900
So we have additional gains, too.

00:13:42.099 --> 00:13:46.219
Right. So as you may know, you can do chapter or section references.

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:50.900
So you can say, hey, in chapter such and such, and then just link to a different chapter

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:55.619
in the Quarto book. You can also do that kind of with different elements within chapters.

00:13:55.960 --> 00:13:57.679
There's also nice equation handling.

00:13:57.679 --> 00:14:01.080
Right. So you can use kind of the latex or equation syntax.

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:02.400
And that works really well.

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:04.200
And we have some documentation about that.

00:14:05.039 --> 00:14:07.080
And then lastly, I think it has a nice hierarchy.

00:14:07.080 --> 00:14:11.440
So we have a table of contents kind of both for the book and for the page.

00:14:11.679 --> 00:14:15.119
So it looks like this. So you can kind of this is a chapter on our Spatial Equity Data

00:14:15.119 --> 00:14:18.119
Tool algorithm. So it's the step by step process of what the tool does.

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:21.000
And it's nice. You can click on the chapters on the side.

00:14:21.159 --> 00:14:24.400
You can also see we have these underlying chapter, chapter six, for example.

00:14:24.419 --> 00:14:25.739
So you can click there and go there.

00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:29.739
And then within within the document, you can go to different subheads.

00:14:29.739 --> 00:14:34.419
So we think that's an easier way for folks to navigate, especially on the web.

00:14:34.739 --> 00:14:38.500
So that was kind of problem solution unexpected day number two.

00:14:39.059 --> 00:14:42.340
Lastly, we have this question. How do we support power user panelists?

00:14:42.739 --> 00:14:46.580
So we think we have or we hope we have users of the tool.

00:14:46.739 --> 00:14:49.179
We also at the Urban Institute use a lot of R.

00:14:49.719 --> 00:14:54.400
So we kind of have these questions where how can we make it easy for users to engage

00:14:54.400 --> 00:14:57.200
with the API and also in the R programming language?

00:14:58.159 --> 00:15:01.719
So the answer is a R package pronounced setter.

00:15:03.039 --> 00:15:08.159
So we have wrapped each API endpoint, of which there are three in

00:15:08.159 --> 00:15:12.159
in our function. So you can kind of engage with it in a nice user friendly way with

00:15:12.159 --> 00:15:13.640
intuitive kind of defaults.

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:17.200
And then we actually have a wrapper function around each of those functions.

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:21.700
So you really can call the spatial equity data tool and then receive the results all

00:15:21.700 --> 00:15:24.500
with one function. So we're really excited about that as well.

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:26.940
OK, so what's our unexpected gain here?

00:15:28.460 --> 00:15:31.780
So the answer is we're kind of living this open source software dream.

00:15:31.780 --> 00:15:36.940
We released this in March and shortly thereafter, we got some

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:41.859
pull requests opened by a really skilled R programmer from

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:45.659
a planning office. So that was really exciting for a couple of reasons.

00:15:45.659 --> 00:15:50.239
The first of which was that just like some of his suggestions made the package itself better.

00:15:50.520 --> 00:15:55.479
And then the second thing is that he actually wrote some functionality for

00:15:55.479 --> 00:15:58.440
the tool to engage with ArcGIS feature layers.

00:15:58.719 --> 00:16:03.520
So kind of zooming out a little bit, my background as a as a data scientist is in kind of

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:05.280
open source software like R and Python.

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:07.719
So I don't have a lot of experience with ArcGIS.

00:16:08.080 --> 00:16:13.200
However, it's really a key workhorse piece of software that folks in planning

00:16:13.219 --> 00:16:18.539
offices use. So we're really excited about this because, you know, we're integrating the

00:16:18.539 --> 00:16:23.500
spatial equity data tool with some software that planning offices who we hope

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:25.539
use our tool kind of use very often.

00:16:25.539 --> 00:16:27.739
So it's kind of this seamless integration.

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:30.659
And this really kind of encapsulated unexpected gains.

00:16:30.659 --> 00:16:34.140
This was really out of the blue. Just one day we get the alert that the pull request was open.

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:36.460
So we were we were really excited about that.

00:16:38.099 --> 00:16:41.099
OK, so what should you take away with talk?

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:46.440
First things first, if you're a person who has the ability to determine where new

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:50.960
resources are allocated across different different geographies, we would encourage you to

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:55.960
use this tool. We also think if you're not that person, but you know people who are, we

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:57.080
would encourage you to share our tool.

00:16:57.080 --> 00:17:00.479
Again, it's free. It's it's open source and you can use it right now.

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:05.880
The second thing is we encourage you to think deeply about what the right tool is for your

00:17:05.880 --> 00:17:10.680
job. So hopefully when you do that, as I've tried to show today, you too may

00:17:10.680 --> 00:17:12.859
experience unexpected gains in your work.

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:14.180
So thank you very much.

00:17:14.180 --> 00:17:15.619
And I'm excited to hear your questions.

00:17:22.380 --> 00:17:27.099
All right, we'll leave this slide up for people who want to take a photo.

00:17:28.020 --> 00:17:32.819
There will be a Slido link for the folks in the audience who want to ask more questions.

00:17:32.819 --> 00:17:37.920
But the first question is, have you looked into other geographic boundaries like police

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:39.900
fire zones or school districts?

00:17:40.040 --> 00:17:41.560
Yeah, so that's a really good question.

00:17:42.439 --> 00:17:47.239
One thing I didn't specifically mention, but the tool has kind of four geographic scales

00:17:47.239 --> 00:17:51.160
that it works on. So it works on the city, the county, the state and the country.

00:17:51.160 --> 00:17:56.280
So if you're working at any of those kind of geographic scales, the tool is ready to go.

00:17:57.199 --> 00:18:00.839
We haven't kind of worked at these other geographies.

00:18:01.719 --> 00:18:04.560
And with the other one that we hear that's very related is like, hey, what if we're a

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:06.959
metro area? It's like a group of three or four counties.

00:18:07.939 --> 00:18:09.219
So we haven't done that.

00:18:09.380 --> 00:18:13.739
I would say kind of that is the next most exciting thing we're excited to develop.

00:18:14.260 --> 00:18:17.780
So hopefully stay tuned and we might have a better answer for you in the next year or two.

00:18:19.060 --> 00:18:20.819
All right, next question.

00:18:20.859 --> 00:18:26.500
Who is your ideal customer for this data and how hard or easy is it to make changes and

00:18:26.500 --> 00:18:27.739
decisions with this data?

00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:31.819
So I think our ideal customer could be really, really anybody.

00:18:31.859 --> 00:18:33.660
And hopefully I wouldn't even say customer, right?

00:18:33.699 --> 00:18:36.780
Like they aren't paying to use this tool.

00:18:36.979 --> 00:18:41.619
But I think our user base, we're hopeful, you know, we could see a lot of people in city or

00:18:41.619 --> 00:18:45.180
municipal governments who are kind of deciding where to use the tool.

00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:51.060
So like if you're kind of approving funding requests for different places or you're kind of

00:18:51.060 --> 00:18:57.140
allocating kind of capital investment, things like that, we think that could be a really

00:18:57.140 --> 00:18:57.979
exciting use case.

00:18:59.819 --> 00:19:01.180
All right, the last question.

00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:07.079
You wrote your documentation in as a Cordo book, but were there any decisions as to why you

00:19:07.079 --> 00:19:10.119
chose Cordo book versus a Cordo website?

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:12.839
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:19:12.839 --> 00:19:16.959
I think I think it was more of eyespace.

00:19:16.959 --> 00:19:22.439
It's like this is a book kind of it felt like, you know, we see these different chapters and I

00:19:22.439 --> 00:19:24.400
don't know, I felt more appropriate for the documentation.

00:19:24.479 --> 00:19:28.560
I can't say maybe we should have thought harder about that, but it seemed it seemed right at

00:19:28.560 --> 00:19:28.880
the time.

00:19:29.859 --> 00:19:30.260
All right.

00:19:30.300 --> 00:19:30.579
Yep.

00:19:30.619 --> 00:19:32.260
So that's all the time we have for you.

00:19:32.260 --> 00:19:34.540
So let's thank Gabe for one more time.

